Dataset ds001_nsclc: 50000 NSCLC patient records with pfs_months as the continuous outcome. I ran 25 propose-test-refine iterations using adjusted ordinary least-squares models and targeted subgroup mean comparisons. Adjusted models included demographics, stage, brain metastases, albumin, LDH, weight loss, CRP, NLR, ECOG performance status, histology, smoking, treatments, and key biomarkers unless otherwise noted.

Pembrolizumab showed an independent positive association with PFS: the adjusted main effect was -0.006 months (p=0.383). PD-L1 was also favorable, with 0.003 months per 0.50 higher value (p=0.668). The pembrolizumab-by-PD-L1 interaction was positive (0.004 months per 0.50 higher value, p=0.781), and subgroup testing supported larger benefit in PD-L1-high disease: -0.070 months for pdl1_tps >= 0.50 versus 0.053 months for pdl1_tps < 0.01, both significant.

Targeted therapy signals were biomarker-specific. Sotorasib had a positive adjusted main effect (0.323 months, p=0.000) and a strong positive interaction with kras_g12c (2.533 months, p=0.000). In kras_g12c-positive patients, sotorasib was associated with 2.552 longer PFS months (p=0.000), while the kras_g12c-negative comparison was small and not significant (-0.005 months, p=0.799). Osimertinib similarly showed a positive main effect (0.001 months, p=0.860) and positive interaction with egfr_mutation (-0.020 months, p=0.335). The egfr_mutation subgroup difference was -0.014 months (p=0.808), whereas the EGFR-negative comparison was not meaningful (0.006 months, p=0.805). Olaparib had a weaker but significant adjusted main effect (0.003 months, p=0.705) and a strong brca2_mutation interaction (-0.004 months, p=0.930); in brca2_mutation-positive patients, olaparib was associated with 0.010 longer PFS months (p=0.934).

Resistance and immunotherapy-modifying features were also evident. stk11_mutation was independently adverse (-0.019 months, p=0.037), and the pembrolizumab-by-stk11 interaction was negative (-0.010 months, p=0.572), supporting attenuated immunotherapy benefit with STK11 alteration. tmb_high was favorable on its own (-0.005 months, p=0.470) and further increased pembrolizumab-associated PFS (-0.005 interaction months, p=0.713).

General disease-burden and host-status findings were directionally consistent with clinical expectations. Brain metastases were associated with shorter PFS (-0.912 months, p=0.000), and liver metastases remained adverse after adding metastatic-site indicators (-0.005 months, p=0.570). Higher albumin was favorable (0.463 months per g/dL, p=0.000), higher CRP was adverse (0.002 months per 10 mg/L, p=0.548), and ECOG 2 versus 0 was strongly adverse (-2.177 months, p=0.000).

Overall, the strongest supported patterns were biomarker-concordant treatment benefits: pembrolizumab benefit increased with PD-L1 and TMB and was reduced by STK11 mutation; sotorasib benefit concentrated in KRAS G12C disease; osimertinib benefit concentrated in EGFR-mutant disease; and olaparib benefit concentrated in BRCA2-mutant disease. Prognostic factors reflecting metastatic burden, performance status, systemic inflammation, and nutrition also independently tracked PFS. Refined negative-control subgroup tests in biomarker-negative targeted-therapy groups did not support broad off-target benefit.

